// _redirects.json — redirect map for originalfreenations.com
//
// Format: JSON5 (https://json5.org) — comments, trailing commas, unquoted keys.
// `from` is a REGEX anchored against the request path; `to` may use $1..$n capture
// groups. `permanent: true` => 301 (default is 302).
//
// This file is the SINGLE SOURCE OF TRUTH. eleventy.config.js parses it at build
// time (so a syntax error fails the build rather than silently shipping no
// redirects), copies it to _site/, and generates _site/xmit.toml from it.
//
// RULES ARE EVALUATED IN ORDER — most specific first.
//
// Derived from the WordPress export (originalfreenations.WordPress.2026-07-08.xml)
// and the SiteSucker crawl of the live site (_raw_archive/originalfreenations.com).
//
// NOT redirected, deliberately:
//   * All 60 post/page slugs — the old site used /%postname%/ and every slug
//     carries over 1:1. Redirecting them would be a no-op at best.
//   * All 100 tag archives — /tag/<slug>/ exists on the new site with the same slugs.
//   * /wp-admin/, /wp-login.php, /xmlrpc.php, /wp-json/* — bot-magnet URLs. Let them
//     404. Redirecting them to / would launder crawl signal onto the homepage.
//   * 77 orphaned WordPress attachment pages (no parent post). A redirect would be a
//     soft-404; an honest 404 is better.
//   * 10 of the 222 old /wp-content/uploads/ URLs — 7 Eventbrite CDN thumbnails and
//     3 favicon variants, all pruned as unused. The other 212 are mapped below.
//
// KNOWN GAP — query-string shortlinks:
//   WordPress always honored /?p=<ID> and /?page_id=<ID>, and 62 such IDs exist
//   (range 23..13174; see the WXR). Those URLs are common in old emails and
//   external links. They are NOT handled here because `from` is matched against the
//   request PATH — a static host has no query string to match on, so no rule in this
//   file can catch them. Fixing it needs either a host-level rule or a small JS
//   shim on the 404 page that reads location.search and forwards. Flagged, not solved.

{
  redirects: [

    // -- Renamed slug ------------------------------------------------------
    // The only _wp_old_slug in the entire export. WordPress served this as a
    // redirect, so it is a live URL in the wild.
    { from: '^/1358-2/?$', to: '/tecumsehs-speech/', permanent: true },

    // -- Feeds -------------------------------------------------------------
    // The old site had 117 feed URLs (root + per category/tag/author). The new
    // site has one. /feed/ is the single highest-value redirect here: every RSS
    // subscriber and aggregator points at it.
    { from: '^/feed/?$', to: '/feed/feed.rss', permanent: true },
    { from: '^/(?:category|tag|author)/[^/]+/feed/?$', to: '/feed/feed.rss', permanent: true },

    // -- Categories --> tags ------------------------------------------------
    // WordPress categories are folded into tags by src/content/posts/posts.11tydata.js
    // (an eleventyComputed that merges `categories` into `tags`), so /tag/<x>/ is
    // built for each of these 12 and the redirect lands on a real archive with the
    // same posts. Counts match the export exactly: doctrine-of-discovery 9,
    // religion 7, biblical 6, politics 6, news 5, culture 5, legal 4, history 2,
    // archive 2, american-dream 1, corona-virus 1, tecumseh-shawnee-leader 1.
    //
    // TWO categories are deliberately NOT mapped to a tag archive:
    //
    //   uncategorized — the big one. WordPress's default term was RENAMED to
    //     "federal Indian law" but KEPT the slug `uncategorized`, and it carries 42
    //     of 57 posts. The converter never wrote it into front matter, so no tag
    //     archive exists (nor should one — it is not a real topic). Goes to /news/.
    //
    //   featured — the theme treats `featured` as an INTERNAL tag and excludes it
    //     from archives, so /tag/featured/ is never built. Falls through to /news/
    //     via the catch-all below. Do not add it to the alternation above; the
    //     redirect would 404.
    { from: '^/category/uncategorized(?:/page/\\d+)?/?$', to: '/news/', permanent: true },
    { from: '^/category/(american-dream|archive|biblical|corona-virus|culture|doctrine-of-discovery|history|legal|news|politics|religion|tecumseh-shawnee-leader)/?$', to: '/tag/$1/', permanent: true },
    // Any category we did not enumerate (or its pagination) — fall back to the list.
    { from: '^/category/[^/]+(?:/page/\\d+)?/?$', to: '/news/', permanent: true },

    // -- Authors -------------------------------------------------------------
    // WordPress used the login in the URL; the new site uses a real slug.
    // /author/haleiwa/ is Steven Newcomb and is the one that matters (55 posts).
    // /author/dave/ never had published content but still resolved with a 200.
    // New author pages do not paginate, so /page/N/ collapses to the archive.
    { from: '^/author/haleiwa(?:/page/\\d+)?/?$', to: '/author/steven-newcomb/', permanent: true },
    { from: '^/author/adamdjbrett(?:/page/\\d+)?/?$', to: '/author/adam-brett/', permanent: true },
    { from: '^/author/dave(?:/page/\\d+)?/?$', to: '/author/david-ratcliffe/', permanent: true },

    // -- Root pagination -----------------------------------------------------
    // Old /page/2..5/ were the homepage archive. The new site paginates at
    // /latest/page/N/, so the shape is preserved and deep links stay meaningful.
    { from: '^/page/(\\d+)/?$', to: '/latest/page/$1/', permanent: true },

    // -- Attachment pages ----------------------------------------------------
    // WordPress published a page per uploaded file. These 82 had a parent post,
    // so they redirect to the post the image belonged to — which is what someone
    // following such a link actually wanted. (The 77 orphans are left to 404.)
